The question of seasonality was bothering me. So, I went through each year from 1991-current and took the final week and compared it to the average for the year. It's 28 years. Of those years, 9/28 (32%) were positive and 19/28 (68%) were negative. Average for all years was -0.14. Average for the negative years was -0.28. Average for positive years was 0.14.

Gasoline price is the result of cost of production, distribution and taxes, adjusted by supply and demand. Main cost of production is naturally the price of oil. Comparing historical price series, I found a very strong correlation between oil [2], [3] and gasoline prices [1], stronger with Brent than WTI. I will use Brent for the calculations.
